Should talk about this MacFarlane article

https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10670-023-00716-0

I agree that beliefs are reasons (against my earlier view), but I think reasons do have a role in individual deliberation as well as in coordination.

The individual/group distinction is a bit porous. We need to coordinate with our later selves - a point that is important from Descartes to Holton.

See also this: https://www.nature.com/nature-index/news/what-scientists-need-to-know-about-fair-data

> Heller agrees. However, the true benefit of FAIR, he argues, is in providing a framework for researchers to manage their own data so they can themselves find it, understand it, and reuse it. "As a scientist, you should treat your data like a love letter to your future self," he says.

